Why Tokens Matter-- 

1. API cost - you pay based on those token counts (with pricing depending on the model and provider).
2. Context Window -If the total exceeds the model's context window, you'll need to shorten or chunk the input.
3. Latency -More tokens generally mean more computation.
4. Performance -Large documents are typically split into chunks before being sent to the model.

"Tokens directly affect four important aspects of an LLM application. First, API cost, because providers charge based on the number of input and output tokens.
Second, context window, since every model has a maximum token limit it can process in a single request. 
Third, latency, because processing more tokens requires more computation and increases response time.
Finally, performance, because sending excessive or irrelevant context can reduce answer quality, whereas sending only relevant information—often using RAG—produces faster, cheaper, and more accurate responses."

[
One important clarification

You may hear people say "more tokens always reduce performance." That's not always true.

If the extra tokens are relevant, they can improve the answer by giving the model more useful context.
If the extra tokens are irrelevant or repetitive, they increase cost and latency and can make it harder for the model to focus on what matters.

]

