What is the difference between GPT, BERT, and LLaMA?

Excellent Answer:

"GPT and LLaMA are decoder-only Transformer models primarily designed for text generation. They are trained using next-token prediction, where the model predicts the next token based on previous tokens.
GPT is developed by OpenAI and is commonly accessed through APIs, while LLaMA is developed by Meta and is open-source, allowing organizations to run and fine-tune it locally.
BERT, on the other hand, is an encoder-only Transformer developed by Google. It is trained using masked language modeling, where it predicts masked words by considering both left and right context simultaneously.
As a result, BERT excels at language understanding tasks such as text classification, sentiment analysis, and named entity recognition, whereas GPT and LLaMA are optimized for generating coherent text."



GPT → typically uses a BPE-based tokenizer.
BERT → uses WordPiece.
Many LLaMA variants → use SentencePiece.


